<h3>Snorkeling at Hikkaduwa</h3>
<p>Explore the vibrant coral reefs and swim with turtles at Hikkaduwa Beach, making snorkeling here a <strong>must-do activity in Sri Lanka</strong> for those who love the ocean.</p>

<h3>Hike Horton Plains and Visit World’s End </h3>
<p>Enjoy a lovely hike in Horton Plains National Park, that leads to World’s End, a dramatic cliff, is a <strong>must-do activity in Sri Lanka</strong> for hikers.</p>

<h3>Visit the Royal Botanical Gardens in Peradeniya</h3>
<p>Stroll through the beautifully landscaped Royal Botanical Gardens in Peradeniya, known for its vast collection of orchids. This is a <strong>must-do activity in Sri Lanka</strong> for nature lovers.</p>

<h3>Explore the Ruins of Polonnaruwa</h3>
<p>Wander through the ancient city of Polonnaruwa, exploring centuries-old temples and ruins. It’s a <strong>must-do activity in Sri Lanka</strong> for people.</p>

<h2>What to eat in Sri Lanka</h2>

<h3>1. Gotu Kola Kanda</h3>
<p>Gotu Kola Kanda is a traditional Sri Lankan herbal porridge made from Gotu Kola (Centella Asiatica), rice, and coconut milk. It's a healthy, nutrient-rich dish consumed for breakfast. The green porridge has a mild flavor and is known for its medicinal properties. It’s a <strong>must-try dish in Sri Lanka</strong> for those who want to experience local, health-focused food.</p>

<h3>2. Seeni Sambal</h3>
<p>Seeni Sambal is a sweet and spicy onion relish made with caramelized onions, chili, and spices. It is often served as an accompaniment to various dishes like rice, bread, or hoppers. The balance of sweetness and heat makes it a <strong>must-try dish in Sri Lanka</strong>, perfect for those who love bold flavors.</p>

<h3>3. Lamprais</h3>
<p>Lamprais is a unique Sri Lankan dish influenced by Dutch Burgher cuisine. It consists of rice cooked in stock, mixed meat curries, and sambals, all wrapped in a banana leaf and baked. This aromatic dish is a must-try in Sri Lanka for those seeking a rich and flavorful meal with a blend of spices and textures.</p>

<h3>4. Fish Ambul Thiyal (Sour Fish Curry)</h3>
<p>Fish Ambul Thiyal is a famous Sri Lankan sour fish curry, often made with tuna. The fish is cooked with a blend of spices and tamarind, giving it a tangy, sour flavor. This dish is one of the must-try dishes in Sri Lanka for seafood lovers, showcasing the country’s coastal influence on its cuisine.</p>

<h3>5. Watalappan</h3>
<p>Watalappan is a traditional Sri Lankan dessert, similar to a spiced coconut custard pudding. Made with coconut milk, jaggery, eggs, and spices like cardamom and nutmeg, it’s a sweet treat often served during special occasions. This decadent dessert is a must-try in Sri Lanka, especially for those with a sweet tooth.</p>

<h3>6. Pol Sambola (Spicy Coconut Garnish)</h3>
<p>Pol Sambola is a spicy coconut garnish made with grated coconut, chili, lime, and onions. It’s typically served with rice, roti, or hoppers, adding a burst of fresh, spicy flavor. As one of the most popular condiments, Pol Sambola is a <strong>must-try dish in Sri Lanka</strong> for spice enthusiasts.</p>

<h3>7. Kiribath (Milk Rice)</h3>
<p>Kiribath, or milk rice, is a traditional Sri Lankan dish made with rice cooked in coconut milk. It’s often prepared for special occasions and served with spicy sambals or curries. Its creamy texture and mild flavor make it a comforting <strong>must-try dish in Sri Lanka</strong> that represents local culture and traditions.</p>

<h3>8. Wood Apple Juice</h3>
<p>Wood apple juice is made from the pulp of the wood apple, a native Sri Lankan fruit with a tangy and sour taste. This refreshing juice is both nutritious and flavorful, making it a must-try beverage in Sri Lanka for those looking to sample unique local fruits.</p>

<h3>9. Hoppers</h3>
<p>Hoppers are a type of bowl-shaped pancake made from a fermented rice flour and coconut milk batter. They come in various forms, such as plain hoppers or egg hoppers (with an egg cooked in the center). Light, crispy, and slightly tangy, hoppers are a must-try in Sri Lanka, especially as a breakfast or dinner item.</p>

<h3>10. Parippu (Dhal Curry)</h3>
<p>Parippu, or dhal curry, is a staple in Sri Lankan cuisine. Made from red lentils cooked with coconut milk, onions, and spices, it’s a comforting and flavorful dish often served with rice or bread. Parippu is a <strong>must-try dish in Sri Lanka</strong>, known for its simplicity and delicious taste.</p>

