<h2>Travel tips for Sri Lanka</h2>
<ul>
	<li>Most travelers need to apply for an Electronic Travel Authorization (ETA) online before arriving.</li>
	<li>The southwest coast is best from November to April, while the northeast coast is ideal from May to September.</li>
	<li>The local currency is the Sri Lankan rupee (LKR). Carry some cash, especially for rural areas.</li>
	<li>When visiting temples or religious sites, cover your shoulders and knees. Remove shoes before entering temples.</li>
	<li>Tuk-tuks are a popular mode of transport for short trips, while buses and trains are great for longer distances.</li>
	<li>When shopping in markets or hiring tuk-tuks, it’s common to negotiate prices.</li>
	<li>Drink bottled or boiled water to avoid potential stomach issues.</li>
	<li>In wildlife areas like national parks, be cautious of elephants and other animals crossing roads.</li>
	<li>A few words in Sinhala or Tamil can go a long way in making connections with locals.</li>
	<li>Be extremely respectful of Sri Lankan traditions, especially during religious ceremonies or festivals. </li>
</ul>


